title: For Sale:  INLAND M1 Carbine 1943, Collector’s Item
postcontent:
Original, all parts marked correctly by/for Inland. From what I have been told this is a true warrior’s carbine and it was kept to show that. This is not an imitation. Not an import, and no rebuilt marks.
This is a rifle kept by a veteran for a lifetime, and due to no heirs, now has come the time to pass it to someone else. This carbine was in the war but it has been kept in excellent condition, and was not shot for many long years.  It has the bayonet lug, the mag release and the rear sights that were added later on by the military.
I am no expert in the field, but I am trying to explain and post pictures with what I have. These are the markings and info about this firearm (I have pictures with all of them):
“Inland Div. 2969XXX” marked under the rear sight on the receiver.
“US Carbine Cal. 30 M1” marked on the receiver, close to the barrel.
“Inland MFG. General Motors, 1-43” is marked on the top at the front of the barrel
“I.R.CO 7160060” marked on the adjustable rear sight. 
Last three markings just mentioned above still have most of the white paint in the groves.
“N” is marked on the front sight.
“Inland” is stamped on the Trigger housing assembly.
“M” is marked on the Magazine catch.
“P.I” is stamped inside the operating slide.
Different numbers marked on the integral gas cylinder.
“KI” is marked on the front band assembly.
“H.I.” is stamped on the hammer.
“M” in a circle is stamped on the safety.
“AI” is stamped on the bolt
“LA” are the last to letters stamped on the firing pin for Rock-Ola. I did not disassemble the bolt, but you can see the letters with the pin assembled. 
“SI” is marked on the oiler
“DI” is marked on the recoil plate
“OI” is marked on the sling well of the stock, and the acceptance “P” mark in a circle is partially visible on the bottom of the stock. No other marks on the stock.
“OI” is marked on the inside (side wall) of the hand guard.
The metal butt plate is original Inland, in perfect like new condition.
The stock is walnut rare high wood, and it is nice, smooth and solid, no cracks or repairs, with only a few old and minor dings. It was cleaned in the past so it might have lost some of its shine. 
The hand guard has two deeper old dents and a minor chip from hitting something either in the war or during transportation somewhere. I took pictures of those so that you can see. These are the only blemishes that I see on the gun.
It also comes with the original magazine pouch that goes over the butt plate. The pouch is marked ”US” on the front and RUBON K.C. 1942 on the back. It is lightly used, but like new.
It comes with two 15 round magazines marked “AI” for Inland. They are used, but in very good condition. 
The original finish on the metal is about 99%.
Bore is shiny with no signs of rust or pitting.
This is a very hard to find original with all the parts made and/or marked by or for Inland.
It also comes with an original bayonet and scabbard.
“USMA8 BMCO” is marked on the scabbard.
“USM4 UTICA” and the flaming bomb are marked on the bayonet guard. One side of the bayonet guard (with the round hole that goes over the barrel), got broke some time in the past, and it looks welded or glued back together. It is not visible unless you look closely.
There is also an original NRA printed booklet about M1 Carbine functions, parts, assembly and disassemble, etc…
The collection comes in a dark brown painted patriotic box that has been equipped with lockable draw bolts, 2 new locks with a key that fits both, and heavy duty handle. The box also serves as a carrying case.
It is a perfect gun for someone who collects these vintage items, or wants to offer a great gift to their father or grandfather that fought in a war for the American flag.
REDACTED
I can send more pictures if I am not able to download all of them on the website, or upon request.
I realize that you can buy a cheaper M1 Inland, but if you want something special, early edition, this is it. I know that an original in mint, almost new condition goes for $2500. I will let this one go for much less.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Red Jacket Firearms ZK-22 Bullpup
postcontent:
As seen on the TV show Suns of Guns!!

This is a completed ZK-22. The ZK-22 is a custom aftermarket stock made by Red Jacket Firearms in Baton Rouge, LA. The stock is a copy of the FN PS90, I've been asked if it was one. The action and barrel are from a Ruger 10/22, so it will always be reliable and will shoot any .22LR rounds you put in it.

The stock moves the action to behind the trigger, making it fit nicer and be more comfortable to shoot. The barrel is still the stock length (18.5in) but since it's moved back, it feels like you have a shorter gun.

There is a top rail for mounting optics. On the front there are nuts preinstalled on either side for attaching accessory rails for lights/lasers/ect.

I have somewhere around 400rds thru it, unsure of how many more (was a used 10/22 before I got it). I cleaned it after every range session, as I do all my guns. It is fun to shoot, lightweight and really accurate (like any Ruger 10/22 would be).

The scope is probably a little much for it. Its a 3-9X zoom, 40mm lens. It's zeroed in at 100yds, which is a little much for a .22lr rifle. The scope is meant for a larger caliber hunting rifle. It was on sale when I was looking, so that's why I have it.
